{
  "doc_id": "37499",
  "text": "Supplemental fat source and interaction between fat source and fat level were detected for yolk cholesterol but not for yolk triglyceride or crude lipids. For yolk cholesterol, fat source was more significant (P ≤ 0.001) than the interaction (P = 0.040) and therefore, main effects are discussed independently of the potential existing interaction [CITATION_1] . Yolk cholesterol in level of F, FL, and R groups were lower (P < 0.001) than C and level of T groups, and the effect of level is significant for fish oil, flaxseed oil, and tallow (Table 4 and Figure 1 ). The total lipid composition of C conformed to a previous study [CITATION_2] , which suggested the reliability of our data. Three sources of fat might reduce yolk cholesterol through inhibiting the activity of 3-hydroxy-3-methyl glutaryl coenzyme A reductase, a key enzyme in cholesterol synthesis [CITATION_3] . No changes were detected in yolk TG and crude fat in all treatments, which is in agreement with [CITATION_4] , while in conflict with [CITATION_5] . Concentration effects were observed for reducing yolk cholesterol in fish oil and flaxseed oil, which is in accordance with previous study [CITATION_6] . The results indicated that fish oil, flaxseed oil, and rapeseed oil could be used as natural feed supplements to produce low-cholesterol duck egg for humans.",
